'''Gita Mohanam''',(गीतमोहनम्) 'Spiritual Hymns' is a book of spiritual poems in Sanskrit written by the Indian poet [[Manmohan Acharya]] and published in 2001. It consists of sixteen songs. Its songs have inspired compositions and choreographic works in [[Odissi]] [[Indian classical dance|classical dance]].

Two songs are written in traditional [[Sanskrit]] meters of Vasanta Tilaka and Pancha Chaamara. Two poems are in the style of [[Rabindra Sangeet]]. The [[Doha]] and [[Chaupai (poetry)|Chaupai]] tradition of [[Tulsi Das]] is also found in two songs in Gitamohanam. Some songs are [[Ragas|Classical Ragas]]. The 10th song ''Jagannatha vandanam'' (Prayer to the God of the Universe) is in both [[Sanskrit]] and [[Oriya language|Oriya]].

The song ''Gajaraja chatwarimsika'' is featured in the 2010 movie [[The Desire]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mohanty|first1=Subhashish|title=Shilpa Shetty takes Odissi lessons for ‘Chindian’ film|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-shilpa-shetty-takes-odissi-lessons-for-chindian-film-1225815|website=DNA India|publisher=Diligent Media Corporation Ltd.|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> Classical music directors including [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]], [[Raghunath Panigrahi]], Guru Ramahari Das, Devashish Sarkar, Laxmikant Palit, Sangeeta Gosain, Suchitra Mohapatra, Sukanta Kundu and Manjushree Tripathy have put songs from the Gitamohanam to music. Dancers including Guru Ratikant Mohapatra, [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] [[Gangadhar Pradhan]] Sujata Mohapatra, Rajashree Praharaj, [[Shilpa Shetty]], [[Dona Ganguly]] and Rahul Acharya have performed to songs from the Gitamonaham.

